<main>
  <h1>IB Chemistry 1.1.3 — Temperature, Kelvin, and Changes of State</h1>
  <div class="byline">Venkata Pendyala</div>
  <hr>

  <h2>1) Big Idea</h2>
  <div class="box">
    <h3>Temperature and Particle Motion</h3>
    <p>
      The absolute temperature \(T\) in kelvin (\(\mathrm{K}\)) measures the <em>average kinetic energy</em> of particles in a substance.
      In microscopic terms, higher \(T\) means particles move faster (on average); lower \(T\) means they move more slowly.
      For an ideal gas, the mean translational kinetic energy per particle is
      \[
        \langle E_k \rangle = \tfrac{3}{2}\,k_\mathrm{B}\,T,
      \]
      where \(k_\mathrm{B}\) is the Boltzmann constant. Per mole, this becomes \(\tfrac{3}{2}RT\) with the gas constant \(R\).
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>2) Why Kelvin?</h2>
  <p>
    The kelvin is the SI unit of temperature. It uses an absolute zero at which, in the idealized model, particles have
    <em>minimum possible</em> kinetic energy. The scale increments are identical to the Celsius degree: a change of
    \(\SI{1}{\celsius}\) equals a change of \(\SI{1}{K}\). The relationship is linear:
  </p>
  <p style="margin-left:12px;">
    \(\displaystyle T(\mathrm{K}) = t(\mathrm{^\circ C}) + 273.15\) &nbsp; and &nbsp;
    \(\displaystyle t(\mathrm{^\circ C}) = T(\mathrm{K}) - 273.15\).
  </p>

  <h3>2.1 A short history</h3>
  <p>
    Early thermometry (Fahrenheit, Celsius) was anchored to convenient reference points (freezing/boiling of water,
    brine mixtures) and instrument behavior (liquid-in-glass expansion). In the 19th century, William Thomson (Lord Kelvin)
    argued for an <em>absolute</em> scale grounded in physics rather than arbitrary points. With the rise of kinetic theory
    (Clausius, Maxwell, Boltzmann), temperature became tied to particle motion and energy. Absolute zero (\(T=0\,\mathrm{K}\))
    marks the theoretical limit where thermal motion is minimized (not “stopped” in the quantum sense, but at the lowest
    energy state allowed).
  </p>

  <h2>3) Observable Changes During Changes of State</h2>
  <p>
    As substances are heated or cooled, we observe macroscopic changes (temperature readings, state, volume, and other physical properties).
    The particle model connects these observations to energy at the microscopic level.
  </p>

  <h3>3.1 Heating and cooling curves</h3>
  <p>
    In a typical heating curve (substance heated at a steady rate):
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Within a single phase</strong> (solid only, liquid only, gas only): the temperature rises as heat increases the
        <em>average kinetic energy</em> of particles. On a graph of \(T\) vs time, this appears as a sloped line.</li>
    <li><strong>During a phase change</strong> (melting, boiling): the temperature stays <em>constant</em> while heat goes into
        changing <em>potential energy</em>—rearranging particles against intermolecular forces. On the graph, this appears as a
        horizontal plateau. The substance absorbs (or releases) energy without a temperature change until the phase transition is complete.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Key distinction:</strong> Temperature reflects <em>average kinetic energy</em>. During phase changes, added or removed energy
    changes <em>potential energy</em> (particle separations/arrangements), not the temperature.
  </div>

  <h3>3.2 What you can see and measure</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Temperature plateaus:</strong> at the melting point and boiling point for a pure substance at fixed pressure.</li>
    <li><strong>State changes:</strong> solid \(\leftrightarrow\) liquid (melting/freezing), liquid \(\leftrightarrow\) gas (boiling/condensation),
        solid \(\leftrightarrow\) gas (sublimation/deposition). The identity of particles (\(\ce{H2O}\), \(\ce{CO2}\), etc.) remains unchanged—these are physical changes.</li>
    <li><strong>Other properties:</strong> density decreases on heating (typically), viscosity of liquids tends to drop with temperature,
        vapor pressure rises with temperature.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>4) Celsius–Kelvin Conversion (and why it matters)</h2>
  <p>
    For chemistry calculations involving temperature in proportional relationships (gas laws, kinetic models), use kelvin.
    This prevents nonsensical results (e.g., doubling \(\SI{10}{\celsius}\) is not physically meaningful, but doubling \(\SI{283.15}{K}\) is a clear ratio).
  </p>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="example">
      <p><strong>Quick conversions</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>\(\SI{25}{\celsius} \; \to\; 25 + 273.15 = \SI{298.15}{K}\)</li>
        <li>\(\SI{-20}{\celsius} \; \to\; -20 + 273.15 = \SI{253.15}{K}\)</li>
        <li>\(\SI{373.15}{K} \; \to\; 373.15 - 273.15 = \SI{100}{\celsius}\)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="example">
      <p><strong>Common pitfalls</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Using Celsius in ideal gas law or kinetic energy formulas—always convert to kelvin.</li>
        <li>Confusing <em>difference</em> vs <em>absolute value</em>: a change of \(\SI{10}{\celsius}\) equals a change of \(\SI{10}{K}\),
            but \(\SI{10}{\celsius}\) is not equal to \(\SI{10}{K}\) as absolute temperatures.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>5) Microscopic View: Kinetic Energy and Temperature</h2>
  <p>
    In gases (well modeled as ideal at low pressure and moderate temperature), particles move freely and rapidly. The Maxwell–Boltzmann
    distribution describes a spread of speeds at any given \(T\); “temperature” corresponds to the distribution’s overall scale (average kinetic energy).
    In condensed phases, motion includes vibrations (solids) and vibrations + translations/rotations (liquids), but the central idea remains:
    higher \(T\) \(\Rightarrow\) higher average kinetic energy.
  </p>
  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Remember:</strong> Temperature is not “heat content.” Heat is energy in transit due to temperature difference; internal energy includes
    both kinetic and potential contributions; temperature connects most directly to the <em>average kinetic</em> part.
  </div>

  <h2>6) Worked Examples</h2>

  <div class="example">
    <p><strong>Example A — Identifying what changes during boiling</strong></p>
    <p>
      Pure water at \(\SI{1}{atm}\) is heated from \(\SI{20}{\celsius}\) to boiling. Once boiling begins, the thermometer reads \(\SI{100}{\celsius}\)
      and stays there until all liquid has vaporized. Why? Because the supplied energy is used to separate molecules (increase potential energy)
      rather than speed them up; the average kinetic energy—and thus the temperature—remains constant during the phase change.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="example">
    <p><strong>Example B — Choosing the correct temperature scale</strong></p>
    <p>
      A gas sample’s volume is proportional to \(T\) (at constant pressure and amount). If the gas is warmed from \(\SI{27}{\celsius}\) to
      \(\SI{54}{\celsius}\), has \(T\) doubled? Converting: \(\SI{27}{\celsius}=\SI{300.15}{K}\), \(\SI{54}{\celsius}=\SI{327.15}{K}\).
      The ratio is \(327.15/300.15 \approx 1.09\), <em>not</em> 2. So the volume increases by about 9%, not 100%.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="example">
    <p><strong>Example C — Celsius–Kelvin conversions in context</strong></p>
    <p>
      Ice and liquid water coexist at \(\SI{0}{\celsius}\) (\(\SI{273.15}{K}\)) at \(\SI{1}{atm}\). Steam and liquid water coexist at
      \(\SI{100}{\celsius}\) (\(\SI{373.15}{K}\)). Note how an equal \(\SI{10}{\celsius}\) rise is an equal \(\SI{10}{K}\) rise—differences are the same in both scales.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>7) Practice Problems</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Convert the following to kelvin and comment on whether each change in temperature would increase average particle kinetic energy:
      <ol type="a">
        <li>\(\SI{-15}{\celsius}\)</li>
        <li>\(\SI{37}{\celsius}\)</li>
        <li>\(\SI{0}{\celsius} \to \SI{25}{\celsius}\) (state whether kinetic energy increases, decreases, or is unchanged)</li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
      A pure substance is heated at constant pressure. The temperature-time graph shows two plateaus: one at \(\SI{0}{\celsius}\),
      another at \(\SI{78}{\celsius}\). Identify each plateau and explain, in particle terms, why the temperature does not rise there.
    </li>
    <li>
      A gas expands from \(\SI{293.15}{K}\) to \(\SI{313.15}{K}\) at constant pressure. By what factor would you expect its volume to change (ideal behavior)?
      Why would using \(\SI{20}{\celsius}\) and \(\SI{40}{\celsius}\) directly give an incorrect factor?
    </li>
    <li>
      In an experiment, a student records the temperature during the melting of a solid and notices small fluctuations around the melting point.
      Give two sensible experimental reasons for these fluctuations and how to minimize them.
    </li>
    <li>
      Distinguish clearly between “heat,” “temperature,” and “internal energy” for a sample of \(\ce{H2O}\) during condensation at \(\SI{100}{\celsius}\).
    </li>
  </ol>

  <div class="muted">
    Notes: Use \(\mathrm{K}\) (not “\(\mathrm{^\circ K}\)”). Differences are the same in \(\mathrm{K}\) and \(\mathrm{^\circ C}\), but absolute values must be in \(\mathrm{K}\) for
    proportional gas/kinetic relations. Physical changes (melting, boiling) do not change chemical identity (\(\ce{H2O}\) remains \(\ce{H2O}\)).
  </div>

